# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sinatra
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sinatra/configuration] Sinatra includes a number of built-in settings that control whether certain features are enabled.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Settings are application-level variables that are modified using one of the `set`, `enable`, or `disable` methods and are available within the request context via the `settings` object.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Applications are free to set custom settings as well as the default, built-in settings provided by the framework.
[src:sinatra/configuration] In its simplest form, the `set` method takes a setting name and value and creates an attribute on the application.
[src:sinatra/configuration] The `/baz` response should come as “baz is set to Hello bar” unless the `foo` setting is modified.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Multiple settings can be set by passing a Hash to `set`.
[src:sinatra/configuration] The `enable` and `disable` methods are sugar for setting a list of settings to `true` or `false`, respectively.
[src:sinatra/configuration] A symbol specifying the deployment environment; typically set to one of `:development`, `:test`, or `:production`.
[src:sinatra/configuration] The `:environment` defaults to the value of the `APP_ENV` environment variable (`ENV['APP_ENV']`), or `:development` when no `APP_ENV` environment variable is set.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Support for signed (but not encrypted), cookie-based sessions are included with Sinatra but are disabled by default.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Sessions are implemented by inserting the `Rack::Session::Cookie` component into the application’s middleware pipeline.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Writes a single line to `STDERR` in Apache common log format when enabled.
[src:sinatra/configuration] This setting is enabled by default in classic style apps and disabled by default in `Sinatra::Base` subclasses.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Internally, the `Rack::CommonLogger` component is used to generate log messages.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Boolean specifying whether the HTTP POST `_method` parameter hack should be enabled.
[src:sinatra/configuration] When `true`, the actual HTTP request method is overridden by the value of the `_method` parameter included in the POST body.
[src:sinatra/configuration] The `_method` hack is used to make POST requests look like other request methods (e.g., `PUT`, `DELETE`) and is typically only needed in shitty environments – like HTML form submission – that do not support the full range of HTTP methods.
[src:sinatra/configuration] The POST `_method` hack is implemented by inserting the `Rack::MethodOverride` component into the middleware pipeline.
[src:sinatra/configuration] The directory used as a base for the application.
[src:sinatra/configuration] By default, this is assumed to be the directory containing the main application file (`:app_file` setting).
[src:sinatra/configuration] The root directory is used to construct the default `:public_folder` and `:views` settings.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Boolean that determines whether static files should be served from the application’s public directory (see the `:public_folder` setting).
[src:sinatra/configuration] When `:static` is truthy, Sinatra will check if a static file exists and serve it before checking for a matching route.
[src:sinatra/configuration] The `:static` setting is enabled by default when the `public` directory exists.
[src:sinatra/configuration] A string specifying the directory where static files should be served from.
[src:sinatra/configuration] By default, this is assumed to be a directory named “public” within the root directory (see the `:root` setting).
[src:sinatra/configuration] A string specifying the directory where view templates are located.
[src:sinatra/configuration] By default, this is assumed to be a directory named “views” within the application’s root directory (see the `:root` setting).
[src:sinatra/configuration] Boolean specifying whether the built-in web server is started after the app is fully loaded.
[src:sinatra/configuration] By default, this setting is enabled only when the `:app_file` matches `$0`. i.e., when running a Sinatra app file directly with `ruby myapp.rb`.
[src:sinatra/configuration] String or Array of Rack server handler names.
[src:sinatra/configuration] When the `:run` setting is enabled, Sinatra will run through the list and start a server with the first available handler.
[src:sinatra/configuration] String specifying the hostname or IP address of the interface to listen on when the `:run` setting is enabled.
[src:sinatra/configuration] The default value in the development environment is `'localhost'` which means the server is only available from the local machine.
[src:sinatra/configuration] In other environments the default is `'0.0.0.0'`, which causes the server to listen on all available interfaces.
[src:sinatra/configuration] This can also be set from the command line with the `-o` option.
[src:sinatra/configuration] If you set the bind option in your application it will override anything set on the command line.
[src:sinatra/configuration] The port that should be used when starting the built-in web server when the `:run` setting is enabled.
[src:sinatra/configuration] The `:app_file` setting is used to calculate the default `:root`, `:public_folder`, and `:views` setting values.
[src:sinatra/configuration] It’s also used to detect whether Sinatra should boot a web server when using classic-style applications.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Boolean specifying whether backtraces are written to `STDERR` when an exception is raised from a route or filter.
[src:sinatra/configuration] This setting is enabled by default in classic style apps.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Boolean specifying whether exceptions raised from routes and filters should escape the application.
[src:sinatra/configuration] When disabled, exceptions are rescued and mapped to error handlers which typically set a 5xx status code and render a custom error page.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Enabling the `:raise_errors` setting causes exceptions to be raised outside of the application where it may be handled by the server handler or Rack middleware, such as `Rack::ShowExceptions` or `Rack::MailExceptions`.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Sinatra can be used in threaded environments where more than a single request is processed at a time.
[src:sinatra/configuration] However, not all applications and libraries are thread-safe and may cause intermittent errors or general weirdness.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Enabling the `:lock` setting causes all requests to synchronize on a mutex lock, ensuring that only a single request is processed at a time.
[src:sinatra/configuration] The `:lock` setting is disabled by default.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Enable error pages that show backtrace and environment information when an unhandled exception occurs.
[src:sinatra/configuration] Enabled in development environments by default.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] The code you changed will not take effect until you restart the server.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Please restart the server every time you change or use a code reloader like rerun or rack-unreloader.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] It is recommended to also run `gem install puma`, which Sinatra will pick up if available.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] In Sinatra, a route is an HTTP method paired with a URL-matching pattern.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Routes are matched in the order they are defined.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] The first route that matches the request is invoked.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] By the way, unless you disable the path traversal attack protection (see below), the request path might be modified before matching against your routes.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] It looks like a condition, but it isn’t one!
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] These options will be merged into the global `:mustermann_opts` hash described below.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] `provides` searches the request’s Accept header.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] The return value of a route block determines at least the response body passed on to the HTTP client or at least the next middleware in the Rack stack.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Most commonly, this is a string, as in the above examples.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] You can also use the `stream` helper method (described below) to reduce boilerplate and embed the streaming logic in the route.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] As shown above, Sinatra ships with built-in support for using String patterns and regular expressions as route matches.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Static files are served from the `./public` directory.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Note that the public directory name is not included in the URL.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] A file `./public/css/style.css` is made available as `http://example.com/css/style.css`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Use the `:static_cache_control` setting (see below) to add `Cache-Control` header info.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Each template language is exposed via its own rendering method.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] This will render `views/index.erb` embedded in the `views/post.erb` (default is `views/layout.erb`, if it exists).
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Options passed to the render method override options set via `set`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] If it's a Symbol, specifies what template to use.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] If you change this, instance variables and helper methods will not be available.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Template engine to use for rendering the layout.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Useful for languages that do not support layouts otherwise.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Defaults to the engine used for the template.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Special options only used for rendering the layout.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Templates are assumed to be located directly under the `./views` directory.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] One important thing to remember is that you always have to reference templates with symbols, even if they’re in a subdirectory (in this case, use: `:'subdir/template'` or `'subdir/template'.to_sym`).
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] You must use a symbol because otherwise rendering methods will render any strings passed to them directly.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Some languages have multiple implementations.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] It also takes a block for inline templates (see example).
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Since you cannot call Ruby methods (except for `yield`) from a Liquid template, you almost always want to pass locals to it.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] It is not possible to call methods from Markdown, nor to pass locals to it.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Since you cannot call Ruby from Markdown, you cannot use layouts written in Markdown.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] However, it is possible to use another rendering engine for the template than for the layout by passing the `:layout_engine` option.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] It is not possible to call methods from RDoc, nor to pass locals to it.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Since you cannot call Ruby from RDoc, you cannot use layouts written in RDoc.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Since you cannot call Ruby methods directly from an AsciiDoc template, you almost always want to pass locals to it.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Templates are evaluated within the same context as route handlers.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] This is typically used when rendering templates as partials from within other templates.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] A layout is usually just a template that calls `yield`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] This code is mostly equivalent to `erb :index, :layout => :post`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Currently, the following rendering methods accept a block: `erb`, `haml`, `liquid`, `slim`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Also, the general `render` method accepts a block.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] NOTE: Inline templates defined in the source file that requires Sinatra are automatically loaded.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Call `enable :inline_templates` explicitly if you have inline templates in other source files.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] If a template named “layout” exists, it will be used each time a template is rendered.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] To associate a file extension with a template engine, use `Tilt.register`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Before filters are evaluated before each request within the same context as the routes will be and can modify the request and response.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] After filters are evaluated after each request within the same context as the routes will be and can also modify the request and response.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Note: Unless you use the `body` method rather than just returning a String from the routes, the body will not yet be available in the after filter, since it is generated later on.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] The effect is the same as including the modules in the application class.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] A session is used to keep state during requests.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] To improve security, the session data in the cookie is signed with a session secret using `HMAC-SHA1`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] This session secret should optimally be a cryptographically secure random value of an appropriate length which for `HMAC-SHA1` is greater than or equal to 64 bytes (512 bits, 128 hex characters).
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] You would be advised not to use a secret that is less than 32 bytes of randomness (256 bits, 64 hex characters).
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] It is therefore **very important** that you don’t just make the secret up, but instead use a secure random number generator to create it.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Humans are extremely bad at generating random values.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] By default, a 32 byte secure random session secret is generated for you by Sinatra, but it will change with every restart of your application.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] If you have multiple instances of your application, and you let Sinatra generate the key, each instance would then have a different session key which is probably not what you want.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] For better security and usability it’s recommended that you generate a secure random secret and store it in an environment variable on each host running your application so that all of your application instances will share the same secret.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] You should periodically rotate this session secret to a new value.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Set a `SESSION_SECRET` environment variable for Sinatra to the value you generated.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Make this value persistent across reboots of your host.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Note that `enable :sessions` actually stores all data in a cookie.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] This might not always be what you want (storing lots of data will increase your traffic, for instance).
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Another option is to **not** call `enable :sessions`, but instead pull in your middleware of choice as you would any other middleware.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] It is important to note that when using this method, session based protection **will not be enabled by default**.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] See ‘Configuring attack protection’ for more information.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] The route block is immediately exited and control continues with the next matching route.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] If no matching route is found, a 404 is returned.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Sometimes `pass` is not what you want, instead, you would like to get the result of calling another route.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Note that in the example above, you would ease testing and increase performance by simply moving `"bar"` into a helper used by both `/foo` and `/bar`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] If you want the request to be sent to the same application instance rather than a duplicate, use `call!` instead of `call`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Check out the Rack specification if you want to learn more about `call`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] It is possible and recommended to set the status code and response body with the return value of the route block.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] However, in some scenarios, you might want to set the body at an arbitrary point in the execution flow.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] You can do so with the `body` helper method.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] It is also possible to pass a block to `body`, which will be executed by the Rack handler (this can be used to implement streaming, see “Return Values”).
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Like `body`, `headers` and `status` with no arguments can be used to access their current values.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Sometimes you want to start sending out data while still generating parts of the response body.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] In extreme examples, you want to keep sending data until the client closes the connection.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] This allows you to implement streaming APIs, Server Sent Events, and can be used as the basis for WebSockets.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] It can also be used to increase throughput if some but not all content depends on a slow resource.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Note that the streaming behavior, especially the number of concurrent requests, highly depends on the webserver used to serve the application.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Some servers might not even support streaming at all.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] If the server does not support streaming, the body will be sent all at once after the block passed to `stream` finishes executing.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Streaming does not work at all with Shotgun.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] If the optional parameter is set to `keep_open`, it will not call `close` on the stream object, allowing you to close it at any later point in the execution flow.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] It’s also possible for the client to close the connection when trying to write to the socket.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Because of this, it’s recommended to check `out.closed?` before trying to write.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] This logger will automatically take your Rack handler’s logging settings into account.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] If logging is disabled, this method will return a dummy object, so you do not have to worry about it in your routes and filters.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] To avoid any logging middleware to be set up, set the `logging` option to `nil`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] However, keep in mind that `logger` will in that case return `nil`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] A common use case is when you want to set your own logger.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Sinatra will use whatever it will find in `env['rack.logger']`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] When using `send_file` or static files you may have mime types Sinatra doesn’t understand.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] It takes reverse proxies and Rack routers into account - if present.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] This method is also aliased to `to` (see below for an example).
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Setting your headers correctly is the foundation for proper HTTP caching.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] To properly use caches, you should consider using `etag` or `last_modified`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] These helpers will not do any caching for you, but rather feed the necessary information to your cache.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Use the `:static_cache_control` setting (see below) to add `Cache-Control` header info to static files.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] According to RFC 2616, your application should behave differently if the If-Match or If-None-Match header is set to `*`, depending on whether the resource requested is already in existence.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Sinatra assumes resources for safe (like get) and idempotent (like put) requests are already in existence, whereas other resources (for instance post requests) are treated as new resources.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] File name to be used in the response, defaults to the real file name.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Value for Last-Modified header, defaults to the file's mtime.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Value for Content-Type header, guessed from the file extension if missing.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Value for Content-Length header, defaults to file size.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Useful when sending a static file as an error page.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] If supported by the Rack handler, other means than streaming from the Ruby process will be used.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] If you use this helper method, Sinatra will automatically handle range requests.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Sinatra offers a `time_for` helper method that generates a Time object from the given value.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] This method is used internally by `expires`, `last_modified` and akin.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] But it is useful that you can actually override this method to hook in your own lookup mechanism.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] You can also easily wrap this up in an extension and share it with others!
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Note that `find_template` does not check if the file really exists but rather calls the given block for all possible paths.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] This is not a performance issue, since `render` will use `break` as soon as a file is found.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Also, template locations (and content) will be cached if you are not running in development mode.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] You should keep that in mind if you write a really crazy method.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Sinatra is using Rack::Protection to defend your application against common, opportunistic attacks.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] By default, Sinatra will only set up session based protection if `:sessions` have been enabled.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Sometimes you may want to set up sessions “outside” of the Sinatra app, such as in the config.ru or with a separate `Rack::Builder` instance.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] If disabled, Sinatra will allow relative redirects, however, Sinatra will no longer conform with RFC 2616 (HTTP 1.1), which only allows absolute redirects.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Enable if your app is running behind a reverse proxy that has not been set up properly.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] helper will automatically add the charset info to.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Path to the main application file, used to detect project root, views and public folder and inline templates.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] if your `environment` is set to development).
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Enabled by default unless environment is "test".
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] You can pass a hash of options to host_authorization, to be used by the Rack::Protection::HostAuthorization middleware.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] The middleware can block requests with unrecognized hostnames, to prevent DNS rebinding and other host header attacks.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] It checks the Host, X-Forwarded-Host and Forwarded headers.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Places a lock around every request, only running processing on request per Ruby process concurrently.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] magic to allow put/delete forms in browsers that don't support it.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] A default hash of options to pass to Mustermann.new when compiling routing paths.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] into redirects if no absolute path is given.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Whether or not to enable web attack protections.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Path to the folder public files are served from.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Disables logs generated by Sinatra's start and stop commands.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Whether or not to reload templates between requests.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Raise unhandled errors (will stop application).
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Any explicitly defined error handlers always override this setting.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] If enabled, Sinatra will handle starting the web server.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Do not enable if using rackup or other means.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Server or list of servers to use for built-in server.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Order indicates priority, default depends on Ruby implementation.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] See 'Using Sessions' section for more information.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Show a stack trace in the browser when an exception happens.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] to trigger app-specified error handling before showing a stack trace in the browser.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Whether Sinatra should handle serving static files.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Disable when using a server able to do this on its own.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Enabled by default in classic style, disabled for modular apps.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Whether Sinatra should handle system signals.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Whether or not to set the X-Cascade header if no route matches.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] There are 2 lifecycle events currently exposed by Sinatra.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] One when the server starts and one when it stops.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Note that these callbacks only work when using Sinatra to start the web server.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] There are three predefined `environments`: `"development"`, `"production"` and `"test"`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] Environments can be set through the `APP_ENV` environment variable.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] In the `"development"` environment all templates are reloaded between requests, and special `not_found` and `error` handlers display stack traces in your browser.
[src:sinatra/intro-p01] In the `"production"` and `"test"` environments, templates are cached by default.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Error handlers run within the same context as routes and before filters, which means you get all the goodies it has to offer, like `haml`, `erb`, `halt`, etc.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] The `error` handler is invoked any time an exception is raised from a route block or a filter.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Sinatra installs special `not_found` and `error` handlers when running under the development environment to display nice stack traces and additional debugging information in your browser.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] When `raise_errors` option is `true`, errors that are unhandled are raised outside of the application.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Additionally, any errors that would have been caught by the catch-all error handler are raised.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] In the `test` environment, `raise_errors` is set to `true` by default.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] This means that in order to write a test for a catch-all error handler, `raise_errors` must temporarily be set to `false` for that particular test.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Sinatra rides on Rack, a minimal standard interface for Ruby web frameworks.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] One of Rack’s most interesting capabilities for application developers is support for “middleware” – components that sit between the server and your application monitoring and/or manipulating the HTTP request/response to provide various types of common functionality.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] The semantics of `use` are identical to those defined for the Rack::Builder DSL (most frequently used from rackup files).
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Rack is distributed with a variety of standard middleware for logging, debugging, URL routing, authentication, and session handling.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Sinatra uses many of these components automatically based on configuration so you typically don’t have to `use` them explicitly.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] You can find useful middleware in rack, rack-contrib, or in the Rack wiki.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Sinatra tests can be written using any Rack-based testing library or framework.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Note: If you are using Sinatra in the modular style, replace `Sinatra::Application` above with the class name of your app.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Defining your app at the top-level works well for micro-apps but has considerable drawbacks when building reusable components such as Rack middleware, Rails metal, simple libraries with a server component, or even Sinatra extensions.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] The top-level assumes a micro-app style configuration (e.g., a single application file, `./public` and `./views` directories, logging, exception detail page, etc.).
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] The methods available to `Sinatra::Base` subclasses are exactly the same as those available via the top-level DSL.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Most options are disabled by default, including the built-in server.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] See Configuring Settings for details on available options and their behavior.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Contrary to common belief, there is nothing wrong with the classic style.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] If it suits your application, you do not have to switch to a modular application.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] The main disadvantage of using the classic style rather than the modular style is that you will only have one Sinatra application per Ruby process.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] If you plan to use more than one, switch to the modular style.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] There is no reason you cannot mix the modular and classic styles.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Not only is Sinatra able to use other Rack middleware, any Sinatra application can, in turn, be added in front of any Rack endpoint as middleware itself.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Sometimes you want to create new applications at runtime without having to assign them to a constant.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] This is especially useful for testing Sinatra extensions or using Sinatra in your own library.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] The scope you are currently in determines what methods and variables are available.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Every Sinatra application corresponds to a subclass of `Sinatra::Base`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] If you are using the top-level DSL (`require 'sinatra'`), then this class is `Sinatra::Application`, otherwise it is the subclass you created explicitly.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] At the class level, you have methods like `get` or `before`, but you cannot access the `request` or `session` objects, as there is only a single application class for all requests.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] For every incoming request, a new instance of your application class is created, and all handler blocks run in that scope.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] From within this scope you can access the `request` and `session` objects or call rendering methods like `erb` or `haml`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] The delegation scope just forwards methods to the class scope.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] However, it does not behave exactly like the class scope, as you do not have the class binding.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Only methods explicitly marked for delegation are available, and you do not share variables/state with the class scope (read: you have a different `self`).
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] You can explicitly add method delegations by calling `Sinatra::Delegator.delegate :method_name`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Have a look at the code for yourself: here’s the Sinatra::Delegator mixin being extending the main object.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Sinatra doesn’t impose any concurrency model but leaves that to the underlying Rack handler (server) like Puma or Falcon.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Sinatra itself is thread-safe, so there won’t be any problem if the Rack handler uses a threaded model of concurrency.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] The latest stable release of TruffleRuby is supported.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] The latest stable release of JRuby is supported.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] It is not recommended to use C extensions with JRuby.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Versions of Ruby before 2.7.8 are no longer supported as of Sinatra 4.0.0.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Sinatra should work on any operating system supported by the chosen Ruby implementation.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Running Sinatra on a not officially supported Ruby flavor means that if things only break there we assume it’s not our issue but theirs.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] If you would like to use Sinatra’s latest bleeding-edge code, feel free to run your application against the main branch, it should be rather stable.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] If you want to run your application with the latest Sinatra, using Bundler is the recommended way.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Note that you will have to list all your application’s dependencies in the `Gemfile`.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Sinatra’s direct dependencies (Rack and Tilt) will, however, be automatically fetched and added by Bundler.
[src:sinatra/intro-p02] Sinatra follows Semantic Versioning, both SemVer and SemVerTag.
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] Rack is used by many Ruby web frameworks and libraries, such as Ruby on Rails and Sinatra.
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] Many Ruby applications are called "rack-compliant".
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] Rack has inspired similar frameworks in JavaScript (jack.js), Clojure, Perl (Plack), Common Lisp (Clack), and .NET (OWIN).
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] The characteristics of a Rack application is that the application object responds to the call method.
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] The call method takes in the environment object as argument and returns the Rack response object.
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] In case the application is being used as a middleware, the environment can have objects that would provide session information, logging capabilities, information on the size of the data that can be used for read and writes etc.
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] In addition to these, the server can store their own data in the environment.
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] The rack server object returns a response which contains three parts: the status, headers and the body.
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] Rack::Response provides a convenient interface to create a Rack response.
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] The class Rack::Response is defined in lib/rack/response.rb.
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] To use the Response class, instantiate it from the middleware layer down the stack.
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] Rack makes it easy to add a chain of middleware components between the application and the web server.
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] Multiple middleware components can be used in the rack which modifies the request/response before handing it over to the next component.
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] The Rack server adds multiple middle middleware by default for the functionalities like showing exception with all the details, validating the request and responses according to the Rack spec etc.
[src:sinatra/rack-web-server-interface] The server for the above code can be initiated using "rackup helloWorld.ru" and can be accessed at http://localhost:9292/ The default port used by the Rack application is 9292.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is interpreted, high-level, and dynamically typed; its interpreter uses garbage collection and just-in-time compilation.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] It supports multiple programming paradigms, including procedural, object-oriented, and functional programming.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] According to the creator, Ruby was influenced by Perl, Smalltalk, Eiffel, Ada, BASIC, and Lisp.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] According to Matsumoto, Ruby was conceived in 1993.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto described Ruby's design as resembling a simple Lisp language at its core, with an object system like that of Smalltalk, blocks inspired by higher-order functions, and practical utility like that of Perl.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] The name "Ruby" originated during an online chat session between Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka on 24 February 1993, before any code had been written.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Two names were initially proposed: "Coral" and "Ruby".
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto chose the latter in a subsequent email to Ishitsuka.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] He also noted that one factor influencing the choice of the name was that a colleague's birthstone was ruby.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] The first public release of Ruby 0.95 was announced on Japanese domestic newsgroups on 21 December 1995.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Subsequently, three more versions of Ruby were released in two days.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] The release coincided with the launch of the Japanese-language *ruby-list* mailing list, which was the first mailing list for the new language.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Already present at this stage of development were many of the features familiar in later releases of Ruby, including object-oriented design, classes with inheritance, mixins, iterators, closures, exception handling and garbage collection.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] After the release of Ruby 0.95 in 1995, several stable versions of Ruby were released in these years.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] In 1997, the first article about Ruby was published on the Web.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] In the same year, Matsumoto was hired by netlab.jp to work on Ruby as a full-time developer.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] In 1998, the Ruby Application Archive was launched by Matsumoto, along with a simple English-language homepage for Ruby.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] In 1999, the first English language mailing list *ruby-talk* began, which signaled a growing interest in the language outside Japan.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] In this same year, Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka wrote the first book on Ruby, *The Object-oriented Scripting Language Ruby* (オブジェクト指向スクリプト言語 Ruby), which was published in Japan in October 1999.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] It would be followed in the early 2000s by around 20 books on Ruby published in Japanese.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] By 2000, Ruby was more popular than Python in Japan.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] In September 2000, the first English language book *Programming Ruby* was printed, which was later freely released to the public, further widening the adoption of Ruby amongst English speakers.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] In early 2002, the English-language *ruby-talk* mailing list was receiving more messages than the Japanese-language *ruby-list*, demonstrating Ruby's increasing popularity in the non-Japanese speaking world.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 was initially released in August 2003, was stable for a long time, and was retired in June 2013.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Although deprecated, there is still code based on it.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 is only partially compatible with Ruby 1.9.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 has been the subject of several industry standards.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] It was accepted as a Japanese Industrial Standard (JIS X 3017) in 2011 and an international standard (ISO/IEC 30170) in 2012.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Around 2005, interest in the Ruby language surged in tandem with Ruby on Rails, a web framework written in Ruby.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Rails is frequently credited with increasing awareness of Ruby.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Effective with Ruby 1.9.3, released 31 October 2011, Ruby switched from being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the GPL to being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the two-clause BSD license.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Adoption of 1.9 was slowed by changes from 1.8 that required many popular third party gems to be rewritten.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.0 was intended to be fully backward compatible with Ruby 1.9.3.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] As of the official 2.0.0 release on 24 February 2013, there were only five known incompatibilities.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Starting with 2.1.0, Ruby's versioning policy changed to be more similar to semantic versioning, although it differs slightly in that minor version increments may be API incompatible.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.2.0 includes speed-ups, bugfixes, and library updates and removes some deprecated APIs.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Most notably, Ruby 2.2.0 introduces changes to memory handling – an incremental garbage collector, support for garbage collection of symbols and the option to compile directly against jemalloc.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] It also contains experimental support for using vfork(2) with system() and spawn(), and added support for the Unicode 7.0 specification.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Since version 2.2.1, Ruby MRI performance on PowerPC64 was improved.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Features that were made obsolete or removed include callcc, the DL library, Digest::HMAC, lib/rational.rb, lib/complex.rb, GServer, Logger::Application as well as various C API functions.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.3.0 includes many performance improvements, updates, and bugfixes including changes to Proc#call, Socket and IO use of exception keywords, Thread#name handling, default passive Net::FTP connections, and Rake being removed from stdlib.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.4.0 includes performance improvements to hash table, Array#max, Array#min, and instance variable access.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.6.0 include an experimental just-in-time compiler (JIT), and *RubyVM::AbstractSyntaxTree* (experimental).
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.7.0 include pattern Matching (experimental), REPL improvements, a compaction GC, and separation of positional and keyword arguments.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0.0 was released on Christmas Day in 2020.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] It is known as Ruby 3x3, which signifies that programs would run three times faster in Ruby 3.0 comparing to Ruby 2.0. and some had already been implemented in intermediate releases on the road from 2 to 3.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] To achieve 3x3, Ruby 3 comes with MJIT, and later YJIT, Just-In-Time Compilers, to make programs faster, although they are described as experimental and remain disabled by default (enabled by flags at runtime).
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Another goal of Ruby 3.0 is to improve concurrency and two more utilities Fibre Scheduler, and experimental Ractor facilitate the goal.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ractor is light-weight and thread-safe as it is achieved by exchanging messages rather than shared objects.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0 introduces RBS language to describe the types of Ruby programs for static analysis.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] It is separated from general Ruby programs.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and library changes in Ruby 3.0 as well.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.1 was released on 25 December 2021.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] It includes YJIT, a new, experimental, Just-In-Time Compiler developed by Shopify, to enhance the performance of real world business applications.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and other improvements in this release.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Network libraries for FTP, SMTP, IMAP, and POP are moved from default gems to bundled gems.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.2 was released on 25 December 2022.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] It brings support for being run inside of a WebAssembly environment via a WASI interface.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Regular expressions also receives some improvements, including a faster, memoized matching algorithm to protect against certain ReDoS attacks, and configurable timeouts for regular expression matching.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Additional debugging and syntax features are also included in this release, which include syntax suggestion, as well as error highlighting.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] The MJIT compiler has been re-implemented as a standard library module, while the YJIT, a Rust-based JIT compiler now supports more architectures on Linux.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 was released on 25 December 2023.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 introduces significant enhancements and performance improvements to the language.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Key features include the introduction of the Prism parser for portable and maintainable parsing, the addition of the pure-Ruby JIT compiler RJIT, and major performance boosts in the YJIT compiler.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Additionally, improvements in memory usage, the introduction of an M:N thread scheduler, and updates to the standard library contribute to a more efficient and developer-friendly Ruby ecosystem.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 was released on 25 December 2024.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 adds `it` block parameter reference, changes Prism as default parser, adds Happy Eyeballs Version 2 support to socket library, improves YJIT, adds modular Garbage Collector and so on.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] It adds experimental ZJIT, a JIT written in Rust, and experimental "Ruby Box", a feature to provide separation about definitions.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] It was decided to bump the version number to 4.0 instead of 3.5 to celebrate Rubys 30. birthday.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto stated that Ruby is designed for programmer productivity and fun, following the principles of good user interface design.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] At a Google Tech Talk in 2008 he said, "I hope to see Ruby help every programmer in the world to be productive, and to enjoy programming, and to be happy.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto has said his primary design goal was to make a language that he himself enjoyed using, by minimizing programmer work and possible confusion.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] If that personal standard remains consistent, there would be few surprises for those familiar with the standard.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is object-oriented: every value is an object, including classes and instances of types that many other languages designate as primitives (such as integers, Booleans, and "null").
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Because everything in Ruby is an object, everything in Ruby has certain built-in abilities called methods.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Every function is a method and methods are always called on an object.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Methods defined at the top level scope become methods of the Object class.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Since this class is an ancestor of every other class, such methods can be called on any object.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] They are also visible in all scopes, effectively serving as "global" procedures.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby supports inheritance with dynamic dispatch, mixins and singleton methods (belonging to, and defined for, a single instance rather than being defined on the class).
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Though Ruby does not support multiple inheritance, classes can import modules as mixins.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] It has support for introspection, reflective programming, metaprogramming, and interpreter-based threads.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby features dynamic typing, and supports parametric polymorphism.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] According to the Ruby FAQ, the syntax is similar to Perl's and the semantics are similar to Smalltalk's, but the design philosophy differs greatly from Python's.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] The syntax of Ruby is broadly similar to that of Perl and Python.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Class and method definitions are signaled by keywords, whereas code blocks can be defined by either keywords or braces.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] In contrast to Perl, variables are not obligatorily prefixed with a sigil.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] When used, the sigil changes the semantics of scope of the variable.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] For practical purposes there is no distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Line breaks are significant and taken as the end of a statement; a semicolon may be equivalently used.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Unlike Python, indentation is not significant.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] One of the differences from Python and Perl is that Ruby keeps all of its instance variables completely private to the class and only exposes them through accessor methods (`attr_writer`, `attr_reader`, etc.).
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Unlike the "getter" and "setter" methods of other languages like C++ or Java, accessor methods in Ruby can be created with a single line of code via metaprogramming; however, accessor methods can also be created in the traditional fashion of C++ and Java.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] As invocation of these methods does not require the use of parentheses, it is trivial to change an instance variable into a full function, without modifying a single line of calling code or having to do any refactoring achieving similar functionality to C# and VB.NET property members.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Python's property descriptors are similar, but come with a trade-off in the development process.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] If one begins in Python by using a publicly exposed instance variable, and later changes the implementation to use a private instance variable exposed through a property descriptor, code internal to the class may need to be adjusted to use the private variable rather than the public property.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby's design forces all instance variables to be private, but also provides a simple way to declare `set` and `get` methods.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] This is in keeping with the idea that in Ruby, one never directly accesses the internal members of a class from outside the class; rather, one passes a message to the class and receives a response.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] The original Ruby interpreter is often referred to as Matz's Ruby Interpreter or MRI.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] This implementation is written in C and uses its own Ruby-specific virtual machine.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] The standardized and retired Ruby 1.8 implementation was written in C, as a single-pass interpreted language.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Starting with Ruby 1.9, and continuing with Ruby 2.x and above, the official Ruby interpreter has been YARV ("Yet Another Ruby VM"), and this implementation has superseded the slower virtual machine used in previous releases of MRI.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] As of 2026, there are a number of alternative implementations of Ruby, including JRuby, Rubinius, and mruby.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Each takes a different approach, with JRuby and Rubinius providing just-in-time compilation and mruby also providing ahead-of-time compilation.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] The maturity of Ruby implementations tends to be measured by their ability to run the Ruby on Rails (Rails) framework, because it is complex to implement and uses many Ruby-specific features.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] The point when a particular implementation achieves this goal is called "the Rails singularity".
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] The reference implementation, JRuby, and Rubinius are all able to run Rails unmodified in a production environment.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto originally developed Ruby on the 4.3BSD-based Sony NEWS-OS 3.x, but later migrated his work to SunOS 4.x, and finally to Linux.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] By 1999, Ruby was known to work across many different operating systems.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Modern Ruby versions and implementations are available on all major desktop, mobile and server-based operating systems.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is also supported across a number of cloud hosting platforms like Jelastic, Heroku, Google Cloud Platform and others.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Tools such as RVM and RBEnv, facilitate installation and partitioning of multiple ruby versions, and multiple 'gemsets' on one machine.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] A Ruby package is called a "gem" and can be installed via the command line.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Most gems are libraries, though a few exist that are applications, such as IDEs.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] There are over 100,000 Ruby gems hosted on RubyGems.org.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] Many new and existing Ruby libraries are hosted on GitHub, a service that offers version control repository hosting for Git.
[src:sinatra/ruby-programming-language] The Ruby Application Archive, which hosted applications, documentation, and libraries for Ruby programming, was maintained until 2013, when its function was transferred to RubyGems.
[src:sinatra/sinatra-software] Designed and developed by Blake Mizerany, Sinatra is small and flexible.
[src:sinatra/sinatra-software] It does not follow the typical model–view–controller pattern used in other frameworks, such as Ruby on Rails.
[src:sinatra/sinatra-software] Instead, Sinatra focuses on "quickly creating web-applications in Ruby with minimal effort." Because of much smaller size compared to Ruby on Rails, it is also called *microframework*.
[src:sinatra/sinatra-software] Some notable companies and institutions that use Sinatra include Apple, BBC, the British Government's Government Digital Service, LinkedIn, the National Security Agency, Engine Yard, Heroku, GitHub, Stripe, and Songbird.
[src:sinatra/sinatra-software] Travis CI provides much of the financial support for Sinatra's development.
[src:sinatra/sinatra-software] Sinatra was created and open-sourced in 2007.
[src:sinatra/sinatra-software] It inspired multiple ports and similar projects in other programming languages, such as Express.js and Scalatra.
[src:sinatra/sinatra-software] Mizerany and Heroku's Adam Wiggins introduced and discussed Sinatra at RubyConf 2008.
